Title: Diagnosis of test `testGenerateURLFragment`
Details: The test `testGenerateURLFragment` checks whether HTML entities such as `"` are correctly escaped to their corresponding character by the `StandardToolTipTagFragmentGenerator.generateToolTipFragment` method. However, the test failure indicates that this is not the case. Following the execution path, we find that `StandardToolTipTagFragmentGenerator.generateToolTipFragment` is not escaping any HTML code; instead, it is using its input `toolTipText` as is. Consequently, un-escaped strings are being returned, which leads to the error demonstrated by the test.

After providing this diagnosis, you will be prompted to suggest which methods would be the best locations to be fixed. The answers should be in the form of `ClassName.MethodName(ArgType1, ArgType2, ...)` without commentary (one per line), as your answer will be automatically processed before finally being presented to the user.

Title: Diagnosis of test `testIssue620`
Details: The test `testIssue620` in the `CodePrinterTest` class of the `com.google.javascript.jscomp` package failed. This test checks the behavior of the `assertPrint` method, which is used to compare the printed output of JavaScript code with an expected string. The failure occurred at line 1283, where the expected output was `alert(/ / / /)` but the actual output was `alert(/ //[]/ /)`.

The `assertPrint` method calls the `parsePrint` method, passing the JavaScript code and a boolean indicating whether pretty printing should be applied. The `parsePrint` method constructs a `CodePrinter` builder and builds the code printer using the provided JavaScript code. Finally, the built code printer is used to print the JavaScript code, and the result is compared to the expected output.

The `parsePrint` method internally calls the `parse` method to parse the JavaScript code into an abstract syntax tree (AST), which is then passed to the code printer. The `parse` method initializes a `Compiler` and `CompilerOptions`, sets the language level to ECMAScript 5, and parses the test code using the compiler. If provided, type checking is performed on the AST. Finally, any unexpected errors or warnings are checked.

Based on the given code snippets, there are no comments available for the methods involved in the failure.

It appears that the failure may be caused by a discrepancy between the expected and actual output of the code printer. It is recommended to investigate the implementation of the `parsePrint` method and the `CodePrinter` builder to determine why the expected output was not obtained.

Methods to be fixed:
- `com.google.javascript.jscomp.CodePrinterTest.parsePrint(java.lang.String, boolean, int)`
- `com.google.javascript.jscomp.CodePrinter.Builder.build()`

Please note that without the corresponding method comments, it is difficult to provide an exact fix.

Based on the available information, provide the signatures of the most likely culprit methods for the bug. Your answer will be processed automatically, so make sure to only answer with the accurate signatures of all likely culprits (in `ClassName.MethodName(ArgType1, ArgType2, ...)` format), without commentary (one per line).
